To add rate limiting to your Express API, you can use the express-rate-limit package. Here's how to do it:

First, install the package:
npm install express-rate-limit

Then import it in your main app file and create a limiter:
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
const limiter = rateLimit({ windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, max: 100 });

Then apply it to all routes:
app.use(limiter);

You can also apply it to specific routes only. Consider storing rate limit data in Redis for multi-instance deployments. The package supports custom error messages and skip functions for health check endpoints. You should also add tests to verify that the 429 status is returned when the limit is exceeded.
